  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Fe-Al ferritic steels with Al > 6.5 wt.% may undergo short-range ordering, increasing brittleness and reducing formability.",
    "κ-carbide precipitation in austenitic steels requires minimum Al and C contents; intragranular precipitation needs Al > 6.2 wt.% and C > 1 wt.% approximately.",
    "Addition of Al decreases Young's modulus: for Fe-Al steels, modulus drops from ~205 GPa at 0% Al to ~153 GPa at 10% Al.",
    "Density of ferrite is 7.85 g/cm³ and austenite 8.15 g/cm³; Al reduces density by about 1.3% per wt.% Al.",
    "In duplex Fe-6.57Al-3.3Mn-0.18C steel, JMatPro calculation shows α fraction increases and γ decreases with temperature between 800–1200 °C.",
    "Low-density duplex and triplex steels exhibit superior strength-ductility balance compared to ferritic steels and many conventional automotive grades, as seen in the banana diagram (Fig. 9).",
    "The synthesis route for bulk low-density steels includes casting, hot rolling at ~900 °C finish rolling temperature, coiling at 400–650 °C, pickling, cold rolling with 66.67% reduction, and continuous annealing at 850–900 °C, sometimes followed by aging at 400–450 °C.",
    "Table I data sources: uniform elongation (UE) values are from literature; normal anisotropy (r-bar) only available for the ferritic IF steel (1.37).",
    "Figure 5 shows phase fractions of Fe-6.57Al-3.3Mn-0.18C alloy calculated by JMatPro; the α phase fraction increases with temperature in the intercritical range, opposite to conventional steels.",
    "Figure 8 shows TEM images of SIP effect in triplex Fe-(26-28)Mn-(11-12)Al-(0.9-1.15)C steel, with shear bands on {111} planes and coherent κ-carbides of 20-30 nm.",
    "Figure 14 shows predicted shell thicknesses for HSLA and low-density duplex steel in Golf V BIW, achieving same torsional stiffness with 14.5% weight reduction."
